						<div class="postbody">A friend and I are working on NES style content in our spare time (though we don't have the talent to make it an actual NES rom) in the vein of Shovel Knight, but more faithful to the hardware. I figured the least best we could do is try to get feedback on the artwork and sprites we have made;<br /><br /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/oHPQKYo.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/rSX8uh7.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/2GSf4QJ.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/kiZdOFG.png" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/JTzD2Tu.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/BXlXkqw.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/qhOcAKL.png" alt="Image" /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/gUK2ilC.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />These are some of the level tiles we have been working on so far. I figured NESdev would be the best place to go for critique to NES accuracy. Using a good looking color palette has also been an issue, but currently we use a palette someone posted here:<br /><img src="http://i49.tinypic.com/spye1c.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/YSwYRep.png" alt="Image" /><br />This was a quick comparison I did of the palette my friend was using:<br /><img src="http://bobrost.com/nes/files/NES_Palette.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />We're both still reading and trying to understand how NES hardware works, so any tips and suggestions would be useful.</div>

