			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Regarding 8*8 or 8*16 sprites, it's only one or the other.  Whether this is global or can change per screen is something I don't know yet.  I do know that there's advantages and disadvantages to each method, but seeing how your graphics look, I'd say that 8*16 would work better.  In short, the advantage of 8*16 is that you can display more with the same limitations, the disadvantage is that it's rather clumsy, especially if you wish to have Megaman/Mr. Gimmick like sprite overlaying for more colors.  With 8*8, a single tile over Megaman's face would have a smaller chance of causing flicker than if it was 8*16, since the sprite is now taller, and the sprites can overlap.<br /><br />Think of it this way.  If you had 9 8*16 sprites lined up so that they rose one pixel each but they have one line in common, they would all flicker.  Think of how Hogan's Alley or Challenger writes Congratulations on screen.<br /><br /><img src="http://img.gamefaqs.net/screens/b/8/e/gfs_18565_3_1.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />The letters don't flicker because they're 8*8, and each letter is moved up one pixel each.  You can have eight letters in a row without flicker, and the next letters would be unaffected by this.  But if those were 8*16 sprites, you couldn't do it this way, the sprites would have to be spaced two pixels taller.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

